Question 1

  1. The model : houseval ~ transit * railtype + density + I(density^2)
  • houseval is the dependent variable. This is the value we hope to predict using the other variables.
  • transit, railtype, and density are independent variables
  • density ^ 2 is a quadratic form of an independent variable. This quadratic term accounts for rate of effect changing as the variable’s value increases or decreases. This allows for non-linearity.

huxreg(
 lm(houseval ~ transit * railtype + density + I(density^2),
data=Californiatod) %>% summary()

CaliforniaTOD <- Californiatod %>% 
  mutate(case_when( 
             railtype == "Light rail" ~ 1, 
             railtype == "Heavy or commuter rail" ~ 0))

CTOD_D <- rename(CaliforniaTOD, "dummy" = 7)

D1 <- CTOD_D %>% 
  subset(dummy == 1)
D2 <- CTOD_D %>% 
  subset(dummy == 0)

lm_D1 <- lm(houseval ~ transit, data = D1)
lm_D2 <- lm(houseval ~ transit, data = D2)

p1 <- ggplot(D1, aes(transit, houseval)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  ggtitle("Light Rail")

p2 <- ggplot(D2, aes(transit, houseval)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  ggtitle("Heavy or Commuter Rail")

Rmisc::multiplot(p1, p2, cols = 2)

Light rail is signifigantly negativly correlated to house value, meaning as house value increases transit decreases. Heavy or Commuter Rail is more signifigantly negativly correlated, meaning as house value increases transit decreases faster than the rate of light rail.

For every one unit increase in transit share the model shows it will increase the housing value by 488,452. This doesn’t make sense because transit share is a percentage and cannot increase by a unit. This isn’t reasonable.

Denisty has no effect on house value.

  1. Because the assumption of the OLS model is the error terms are identicaly independently normally distributed we need understand variable interactions to determine if transformation is needed to satisfy this assumption. A simply way to do this is visualizing the variables in scatter plots.
s1 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(transit, houseval)) + geom_point()
s2 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(railtype, houseval)) + geom_point()
s3 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(density, houseval)) + geom_point()
s4 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(I(density^2), houseval)) + geom_point()

Rmisc::multiplot(s2, s4, s1, s3, cols = 2)

According to the plots none of the variables look to be normally distributed. To create the best model some data transformation tests are needed. The most simple test is to transform the dependent variable, house value.

s1 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(transit, log(houseval))) + geom_point()
s2 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(railtype, log(houseval))) + geom_point()
s3 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(density, log(houseval))) + geom_point()
s4 <- ggplot(CTOD_D, aes(region, log(houseval))) + geom_point()

Rmisc::multiplot(s2, s4, s1, s3, cols = 2)

Using a log transformation on house value makes density and transit variables much more normally distributed. A R-squared test is needed to determine if this is actually a better model. Because the visual testing isn’t enough to determine region or railtype variables, r-squared testing will be used there as well.

lm1.1 <- lm(houseval ~ transit, data = CTOD_D)
lm1.2 <- lm(log(houseval) ~ transit, data = CTOD_D)

lm1.1 : Multiple R-squared: 0.01616, Adjusted R-squared: -0.02483 lm1.2 : Multiple R-squared: 0.0002866, Adjusted R-squared: -0.04137

lm1.1, no data transformation, is a better model, although the effect size is very small.

lm2.1 <- lm(houseval ~ density, data = CTOD_D)
lm2.2 <- lm(log(houseval) ~ density, data = CTOD_D)

lm2.1 : Multiple R-squared: 0.0006972, Adjusted R-squared: -0.04094 lm2.2 : Multiple R-squared: 0.002562, Adjusted R-squared: -0.039

lm2.2, log of house value, is a better model. The effect size is very small.

lm3.1 <- lm(houseval ~ railtype, data = CTOD_D)
lm3.2 <- lm(log(houseval) ~ railtype, data = CTOD_D)

lm3.1 : Multiple R-squared: 0.2451, Adjusted R-squared: 0.2137 lm3.2 : Multiple R-squared: 0.4008, Adjusted R-squared: 0.3759

lm3.2, log of house value, is a better model. The effect of rail type on house value is signifigant, explaining 40% the variation from the conditional mean.

lm4.1 <- lm(houseval ~ region, data = CTOD_D)
lm4.2 <- lm(log(houseval) ~ region, data = CTOD_D)

lm4.1: Multiple R-squared: 0.2896, Adjusted R-squared: 0.1928 lm4.2: Multiple R-squared: 0.4122, Adjusted R-squared: 0.332

lm4.2, log of house value, is a better model, and the effect is signifigant.

Although the interaction of house value and transit is a better fit without transforming house value using log, the overall model is a better fit transforming house value using log and the signifigance of these variables is much higher than the one variable that was more significant without the transformation. Another regression test can prove this:

lm5.1 <- lm(houseval ~ transit + density + railtype, data = CTOD_D)
lm5.2 <- lm(log(houseval) ~ transit + density + railtype, data = CTOD_D)

lm5.1 : Multiple R-squared: 0.6723, Adjusted R-squared: 0.5689 lm5.2 : Multiple R-squared: 0.7359, Adjusted R-squared: 0.6525

lm5.2 is a better fit. This model explains 74% of the variation of House Value (Y, or dependent variable), around the unconditional mean.

  1. A model that explains 75% of the variations around the conditional mean is a very good model. Transit accessibility and density had the lowest (negligible) effect on hosue value. Region (neighborhood/city) was the most signifigant varible in this set, followed closely by rail type. The model concludes the city is the most impactful on house value, followed by proximity of light rail, distantly trailed by density and transit.

  2. Other factors that are commonly used to predict house value is the average age of the house, the average size of the house, average age of person living in the neighborhood (to understand if kids are a factor), and school quality. I expect high quality schools and proximity of lower-aged home owners to increase the house value. I think the age of the house could have a quadratic form, meaning a very old house and a very new house could have high values, but middle-aged houses would have a lower value. I expect this effect to be more signifigant than transit accessibility, especially in the US, and very much more so in places like LA that have no cultural dependence on transit.
